by not being sustainable
about what we eat.

00:12:42.220 --> 00:12:45.130
Sushi, Poke, all those
type of restaurants

00:12:45.130 --> 00:12:47.110
are contributing
to this problem,

00:12:47.110 --> 00:12:50.140
killing not only tunas,
but killing sharks,

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:52.630
and sea turtles, and seabirds.

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:55.960
I think that there's hope, in
the sense that we have places

00:12:55.960 --> 00:12:59.530
like Google, which are using
their tremendous resources

00:12:59.530 --> 00:13:02.320
right now, not only
to do searches that

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:05.000
help us understand
what we're looking for,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.630
but also creating
transparency in the ocean

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:10.960
through Google Oceans
and Global Fish Watch,

00:13:10.960 --> 00:13:14.740
creating a capacity to now
see where humans are impacting

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:18.110
the planet in a way that we've
never been able to see before.

00:13:18.110 --> 00:13:20.110
So we're able to turn
on the light switch

00:13:20.110 --> 00:13:21.310
and see where humans are.

00:13:21.310 --> 00:13:24.910
And if we can use
big data crunching

00:13:24.910 --> 00:13:30.190
combining fish and ships
as well as fish and chips,

00:13:30.190 --> 00:13:32.260
we'll be able to
potentially get our hands

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:33.920
on some of these problems.

00:13:33.920 --> 00:13:36.640
DAVID HELVARG: And I think
with my background 30 years

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:39.310
as a journalist, I
can't be eco-optimist,

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:44.110
but what I do say is, we're
now at this stage of triage.

00:13:44.110 --> 00:13:46.450
That we're going to save
what we can while we can.

00:13:46.450 --> 00:13:50.260
The IPCC report in
2018 says that if we

00:13:50.260 --> 00:13:54.850
can keep temperatures
to 1.5 degrees Celsius,

00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:58.990
we can save perhaps 10% of
our living coral reef systems.

00:13:58.990 --> 00:14:01.340
If it goes over two
degrees, we lose it.

00:14:01.340 --> 00:14:04.690
And so, with existential
threats like this,

00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:06.130
we need big responses.

00:14:06.130 --> 00:14:08.500
I mean, right now I'm
working on the Blue New

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:10.267
Deal, the ocean
and coastal aspects

00:14:10.267 --> 00:14:11.350
that we want to integrate.

00:14:11.350 --> 00:14:14.350
And I'm going back
east to DC on Wednesday

00:14:14.350 --> 00:14:17.590
to talk to the people who
introduced the Green New

00:14:17.590 --> 00:14:19.130
Deal, which is a great concept.

00:14:19.130 --> 00:14:21.970
By the time there's hopefully
a change in government,

00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:25.930
and we hit the road, hit the
ground running in January 2021,

00:14:25.930 --> 00:14:29.350
with real legislation to really
do the transition that science

00:14:29.350 --> 00:14:31.300
tells us we have to.

00:14:31.300 --> 00:14:32.800
ANA BLANCO: And
then to add to that,

00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:37.030
I think we're very well-versed
and knowledgeable about what's

00:14:37.030 --> 00:14:39.400
happening in the ocean,
and really appreciate

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:41.740
this opportunity to
share what we know.

00:14:41.740 --> 00:14:43.420
And one thing that
keeps popping up

00:14:43.420 --> 00:14:45.510
that I'm reading
a lot more about

00:14:45.510 --> 00:14:48.113
is the increase in population.

00:14:48.113 --> 00:14:49.780
Because, we as humans,
are the ones that

00:14:49.780 --> 00:14:51.660
are doing most of the damage.

00:14:51.660 --> 00:14:53.810
And we are the ones that
need to be educated.

00:14:53.810 --> 00:14:57.190
But with the increase
in population, and just

00:14:57.190 --> 00:15:01.000
it's taking its toll
on the finite resources

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.060
that this planet has to offer.

00:15:03.060 --> 00:15:06.070
So I think that is
another component that

00:15:06.070 --> 00:15:07.750
plays into all of
this, that we need

00:15:07.750 --> 00:15:10.587
to start talking about as well.

00:15:10.587 --> 00:15:12.670
MICHIEL BAKKER: You are
the experts in this field.

00:15:12.670 --> 00:15:15.040
As a layperson on
the outside, what

00:15:15.040 --> 00:15:18.040
do you think we should know
being the three largest

00:15:18.040 --> 00:15:21.323
challenges we're faced
with with the oceans?

00:15:21.323 --> 00:15:22.240
I know there are more.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:24.920
But if you would say, if we
could only fix the first three,

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:28.600
what would those first three be?

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:30.490
ANA BLANCO: Should we
huddle first, and then

00:15:30.490 --> 00:15:32.282
decide which ones we want--

00:15:32.282 --> 00:15:34.240
BIRGITTE RASINE: I think
that one thing that we

00:15:34.240 --> 00:15:36.835
have to fix, or not fix,
but actually establish

00:15:36.835 --> 00:15:40.540
is a relationship
between us and the ocean.

00:15:40.540 --> 00:15:43.240
I think, Kyle, you brought
up the point of how

00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:45.403
come we didn't really
have so much pickup

00:15:45.403 --> 00:15:46.820
in the media about
climate change,

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:48.110
and now plastic pollution?

00:15:48.110 --> 00:15:50.590
Well, the reason is because
every one of us uses plastic.

00:15:50.590 --> 00:15:54.030
It's something that-- it's
our children's birthday toys.

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:55.840
It's our plastic knives.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:58.820
It's lots of--
chairs in this room.

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:01.570
So unless and until we can
start connecting those dots

00:16:01.570 --> 00:16:03.708
and make it very
personal, something

00:16:03.708 --> 00:16:05.750
that we care-- because
what do people care about?

00:16:05.750 --> 00:16:07.040
They care about their health.

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:09.460
They care about their
finances, our children,

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:11.860
things that are near
and dear to us, right?

00:16:11.860 --> 00:16:15.610
So we have to find those
things that make the ocean near

00:16:15.610 --> 00:16:17.270
and dear to us.

00:16:17.270 --> 00:16:18.250
So that would be--

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:19.667
DAVID HELVARG: Not
three, but when

00:16:19.667 --> 00:16:21.900
I wrote "50 Ways
to Save the Ocean,"

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:23.770
number one is go to
the beach, because you

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:25.340
protect what you love.

00:16:25.340 --> 00:16:28.210
And I think that's why
things work in California,

00:16:28.210 --> 00:16:30.790
because Californians have
the sense of entitlement

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:34.330
to the beach and ocean,
because we have the access.

00:16:34.330 --> 00:16:36.438
BARBARA BLOCK: I think we
have to eat sustainably.

00:16:36.438 --> 00:16:38.230
So we've got to figure
out what that means,

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:39.940
both on land and sea.

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:44.080
And when you see that brand new
Poke restaurant down street,

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:47.530
start asking the question,
when you put a piece of tuna

00:16:47.530 --> 00:16:50.230
in your mouth, where
did that tuna come from?

00:16:50.230 --> 00:16:53.320
We don't put beef in
our mouth and do it

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:57.740
without knowing where's this
beef from, what type of animal

00:16:57.740 --> 00:16:58.240
is it.

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:02.030
And yet, we do this with
ocean food all the time.

00:17:02.030 --> 00:17:04.599
So I want everyone
to take a moment

00:17:04.599 --> 00:17:07.480
and think about what
is it I'm eating.

00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:09.532
And has it been
caught sustainably?

00:17:09.532 --> 00:17:10.990
Is it something I
should be eating?

00:17:10.990 --> 00:17:13.270
And what kind of waters
did it come out of?

00:17:13.270 --> 00:17:15.369
DAVID HELVARG: I was at
the Our Ocean Conference

00:17:15.369 --> 00:17:18.099
that John Kerry put on when
he was Secretary of State.

00:17:18.099 --> 00:17:20.190
Sylvia Earle came late
to the lunch table.

00:17:20.190 --> 00:17:23.274
And there's just one
tray left with sort

00:17:23.274 --> 00:17:25.015
of fillets labeled fish.

00:17:25.015 --> 00:17:26.140
She goes what kind of fish?

00:17:26.140 --> 00:17:28.265
I go, oh, there's the
Assistant Secretary of State,

00:17:28.265 --> 00:17:29.410
let's go ask her.

00:17:29.410 --> 00:17:31.915
Drag her over,
and she goes, um--

00:17:31.915 --> 00:17:33.940
Sylvia's like,
it's labeled fish.

00:17:33.940 --> 00:17:36.050
She goes, well, I
asked the caterers

00:17:36.050 --> 00:17:37.480
to make sure it was sustainable.

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:39.110
She says, but it's labeled fish.

00:17:39.110 --> 00:17:41.662
The chicken's not labeled bird.

00:17:41.662 --> 00:17:44.125
BARBARA BLOCK: [LAUGHS] The
chicken's not labeled bird.

00:17:44.125 --> 00:17:46.000
KYLE VAN HOUTAN: I think
what everyone's said

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:47.010
is obviously important.

00:17:47.010 --> 00:17:48.760
Climate change, I think
we probably agree,

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:52.630
is the number one threat facing
the ocean and the planet.

00:17:52.630 --> 00:17:55.870
Sustainable fishing is
absolutely up there.

00:17:55.870 --> 00:17:59.710
And I think that just from a
sheer scientific standpoint,

00:17:59.710 --> 00:18:02.050
I would say marine
pollution, and sewage,

00:18:02.050 --> 00:18:04.930
and plastic as part of that,
has got to be up there.

00:18:04.930 --> 00:18:09.850
And Aldo Leopold
said that we love--

00:18:09.850 --> 00:18:12.100
we grow to love
what we understand.

00:18:12.100 --> 00:18:14.260
And by engaging California--

00:18:14.260 --> 00:18:16.070
I mean, I'm not from California.

00:18:16.070 --> 00:18:18.610
But one of the fascinating
things about coming here

00:18:18.610 --> 00:18:21.610
a couple of decades ago is
that the dream of California

00:18:21.610 --> 00:18:28.330
seems to me, the coexistence
of relatively pristine nature

00:18:28.330 --> 00:18:30.670
and the most advanced
technological society

00:18:30.670 --> 00:18:32.920
that we have right
here in the Bay Area.

00:18:32.920 --> 00:18:34.660
We have this
wonderful open space.

00:18:34.660 --> 00:18:36.500
And we didn't have
that by accident.

00:18:36.500 --> 00:18:38.530
We had that on purpose,
because people loved

00:18:38.530 --> 00:18:39.943
the open space and the coast.

00:18:39.943 --> 00:18:41.860
And we have this California
Coastal Commission

00:18:41.860 --> 00:18:43.630
who vehemently defends that.

00:18:43.630 --> 00:18:46.030
And that is the essence of
like Surfrider Foundation

00:18:46.030 --> 00:18:47.350
and organizations like that.

00:18:47.350 --> 00:18:48.365
I'm a surfer.

00:18:48.365 --> 00:18:49.990
I don't surf on
certain days, because I

00:18:49.990 --> 00:18:53.500
don't want the pollution in the
water, to get sick from that.

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:55.480
And just engaging and
taking care of the place

00:18:55.480 --> 00:18:58.300
where you are, I think,
is absolutely critical.

00:18:58.300 --> 00:19:00.430
DAVID HELVARG: And when I
wrote "The Golden Shore,

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:02.305
California's Love Affair
with the Sea," which

00:19:02.305 --> 00:19:04.750
I won't flash up here.

00:19:04.750 --> 00:19:07.900
But basically, I'd been in DC
nine years, and I came home.

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:10.120
And a lot of what we did
with Blue Frontiers, how

00:19:10.120 --> 00:19:12.080
do we scale up
solutions in time.

00:19:12.080 --> 00:19:14.830
And I realized, California
is a solution at scale.

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:16.360
We're 40 million people.

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:18.660
We're the world's
fifth largest economy.

00:19:18.660 --> 00:19:20.620
And we do pretty good
with our coast and ocean,

00:19:20.620 --> 00:19:23.090
because there's that
sense of entitlement.

00:19:23.090 --> 00:19:25.810
And I also think there's this
democracy of blue interest,

00:19:25.810 --> 00:19:28.780
because you have
conservationists, and surfers,

00:19:28.780 --> 00:19:31.780
and fishermen, and the
Navy, and the ports,

00:19:31.780 --> 00:19:34.912
and all these different
interests that value.

00:19:34.912 --> 00:19:36.370
And when you do
right by the ocean,

00:19:36.370 --> 00:19:38.350
you find out it does
good by your economy

00:19:38.350 --> 00:19:41.075
and everything else.

00:19:41.075 --> 00:19:42.200
Ask yourself this question.

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:44.750
To Barbara and to
Richard as well.

00:19:44.750 --> 00:19:49.120
So this notion of does what I
eat really make a difference,

00:19:49.120 --> 00:19:51.760
and does one person
really make a difference.

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:55.270
So when you talk about
knowing what you eat,

00:19:55.270 --> 00:19:57.802
sushi, poke, you
it might be, how

00:19:57.802 --> 00:19:59.260
would you deal with
an individual's

00:19:59.260 --> 00:20:01.960
who's going to pose you the
question, my individual actions

00:20:01.960 --> 00:20:04.420
don't really make a
difference, because I'm one

00:20:04.420 --> 00:20:06.710
of know seven billion people.

00:20:06.710 --> 00:20:08.630
How do you ultimately
touch that individual,

00:20:08.630 --> 00:20:13.270
and make him or her believe
that his or her actions do

00:20:13.270 --> 00:20:14.367
make a difference?

00:20:14.367 --> 00:20:16.450
BIRGITTE RASINE: Well, I
would say that you're not

00:20:16.450 --> 00:20:17.470
just one person.

00:20:17.470 --> 00:20:19.150
You're one of seven billion.

00:20:19.150 --> 00:20:21.750
So the more of us
that think like that,

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:24.802
it's going to be seven billion
people thinking like this.

00:20:24.802 --> 00:20:25.760
BARBARA BLOCK: I agree.

00:20:25.760 --> 00:20:27.430
I mean, we've lost
our connection

00:20:27.430 --> 00:20:29.030
to the natural world.

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:31.030
It's happening
all the time as we

00:20:31.030 --> 00:20:34.570
evolve on this planet
as a human species.

00:20:34.570 --> 00:20:38.200
I think that the more that we
can understand that individuals

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:40.870
make a difference
through both education,

00:20:40.870 --> 00:20:45.130
such as the aquarium, or through
youth programs, connecting

00:20:45.130 --> 00:20:48.730
humans to the sea, humans
to the land, the better

00:20:48.730 --> 00:20:50.140
off this planet will be.

00:20:50.140 --> 00:20:53.770
Because that's what we've
lost across the globe.

00:20:53.770 --> 00:20:56.020
And the more we interact
with technology,

00:20:56.020 --> 00:20:58.730
the less we interact
with the world around us.

00:20:58.730 --> 00:21:00.855
BIRGITTE RASINE: And that's
why like, you guys know

00:21:00.855 --> 00:21:01.780
that Instagram egg?

00:21:01.780 --> 00:21:03.460
How many of you have seen that?

00:21:03.460 --> 00:21:06.950
The one that garnered more, like
the most Instagram likes ever.

00:21:06.950 --> 00:21:09.200
And so I think, well, if I
were that one person liking

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:11.492
that egg, I could have said,
well, I'm just one person.

00:21:11.492 --> 00:21:14.090
I'm not going to make a change
in how many likes this egg has.

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:17.530
And yet, we've got 35 or
50 million likes, right?

00:21:17.530 --> 00:21:20.060
So we've just got to
find that thing that

00:21:20.060 --> 00:21:22.040
makes us hit like on the ocean.

00:21:22.040 --> 00:21:25.830
DAVID HELVARG: In French, they
say that one egg is enough.

00:21:25.830 --> 00:21:30.120
But it's really, it's
this false dichotomy.

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:32.420
I can't help myself.

00:21:32.420 --> 00:21:34.670
People say, well, is it the
personal or the political?

00:21:34.670 --> 00:21:38.210
And it's like saying do you quit
smoking or fight big tobacco?

00:21:38.210 --> 00:21:40.220
I mean, I don't eat sushi.

00:21:40.220 --> 00:21:42.650
And then we had a
healthy ocean hill day

00:21:42.650 --> 00:21:46.700
where we lobbied and helped
pass an IUU pirate fishing bill,

00:21:46.700 --> 00:21:49.040
so that we don't
deplete the ocean.

00:21:49.040 --> 00:21:52.880
I mean, your individual
acts, the things you do,

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:57.470
inspire you to engage
with the larger world.

00:21:57.470 --> 00:21:59.700
MICHIEL BAKKER: So how do
you engage your audience?

00:21:59.700 --> 00:22:01.408
So how do you get
people actually excited

00:22:01.408 --> 00:22:04.460
about your world versus
so many other worlds

00:22:04.460 --> 00:22:08.840
that are screaming for attention
and for activism as well?

00:22:08.840 --> 00:22:11.150
Maybe, for you, David.

00:22:11.150 --> 00:22:12.650
DAVID HELVARG: Start
with people who

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:14.390
love the ocean, who
live by the ocean.

00:22:14.390 --> 00:22:18.780
We try and build a constituency.

00:22:18.780 --> 00:22:20.810
We bring every two
years, except this year,

00:22:20.810 --> 00:22:22.040
because it's useless.

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:25.700
Bring people together in
DC from around the ocean,

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:27.920
connect Maritime
conservationists

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:29.780
with Maritime communities.

00:22:29.780 --> 00:22:32.900
Realize they have allies in
places like big institutions,

00:22:32.900 --> 00:22:35.270
like the Monterey Aquarium,
the National Aquarium.

00:22:35.270 --> 00:22:39.020
That they have allies with the
Commandant of the Coast Guard,

00:22:39.020 --> 00:22:42.050
or with Senators
Whitehouse or Markey.

00:22:42.050 --> 00:22:43.260
And go on the Hill.

00:22:43.260 --> 00:22:45.500
We've had Healthy
Ocean Hill Days,

00:22:45.500 --> 00:22:47.510
where we've had 26
state delegations,

00:22:47.510 --> 00:22:49.880
and the third biggest
was from Colorado,

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:54.230
because in April, we're going
to have an inland ocean Action

00:22:54.230 --> 00:22:55.310
Summit in Dallas.

00:22:55.310 --> 00:22:57.770
And we're going to try and
grow the inland ocean movement,

00:22:57.770 --> 00:23:00.680
and make people realize every
state's a coastal state.

00:23:00.680 --> 00:23:01.880
You connect up.

00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:04.140
It starts, like I say,
number one's go to the beach.

00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:06.680
It starts with people who
love, and care, and depend

00:23:06.680 --> 00:23:08.690
for their livelihoods
on the ocean.

00:23:08.690 --> 00:23:11.570
And then you just try
and do whatever you can,

00:23:11.570 --> 00:23:15.320
and use whatever tools you
have, to connect with people.

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:18.020
Tools like the International
Ocean Film Festival

00:23:18.020 --> 00:23:20.120
and the tools of science.

00:23:20.120 --> 00:23:23.360
And make science
exciting, the way Barbara

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:25.340
gets to commune with
great white sharks.

00:23:25.340 --> 00:23:27.255
And one of the
things in California

00:23:27.255 --> 00:23:28.130
is, we're not afraid.

00:23:28.130 --> 00:23:29.588
There's a sense
that if there's not

00:23:29.588 --> 00:23:31.760
something bigger and
meaner than you out there,

00:23:31.760 --> 00:23:33.710
it's not really wilderness.

00:23:33.710 --> 00:23:35.720
And I think that just
making those connections.

00:23:35.720 --> 00:23:38.570
I always talk about
our job in the US

00:23:38.570 --> 00:23:41.390
is to restore the blue and
our red, white, and blue.

00:23:41.390 --> 00:23:44.860
It's patriotic not to
pollute our living seas.

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:46.640
ANA BLANCO: And I
want to add to that.

00:23:46.640 --> 00:23:49.400
I actually went with
David to Washington, DC,

00:23:49.400 --> 00:23:50.960
for one of his Blue
Vision Summits.

00:23:50.960 --> 00:23:52.918
I can't remember how many
years ago it was now.

00:23:52.918 --> 00:23:55.890
But there were so many people
from all over the country.

00:23:55.890 --> 00:23:59.520
And we had the opportunity
to meet with our legislators.

00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:02.540
And we were discussing the
ocean policy back then.

00:24:02.540 --> 00:24:04.830
And we had three things that
we wanted to talk about.

00:24:04.830 --> 00:24:08.360
And it was my first time,
actually, being on the Hill.

00:24:08.360 --> 00:24:13.470
And actually being able
to talk to my legislators.

00:24:13.470 --> 00:24:15.950
And I was so impressed
with the impact

00:24:15.950 --> 00:24:19.940
that we had as a group, coming
from across the United States,

00:24:19.940 --> 00:24:23.720
and having a voice, and
communicating our interests

00:24:23.720 --> 00:24:24.560
and what we needed.

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:28.700
So getting people together and
getting that voice out there

00:24:28.700 --> 00:24:30.260
is what David does.

00:24:30.260 --> 00:24:32.690
And we do it with the
film festival as well.

00:24:32.690 --> 00:24:35.240
So we provide a
platform for people

00:24:35.240 --> 00:24:37.730
to come together and
talk about the ocean.

00:24:37.730 --> 00:24:39.680
And we show films
from around the world.

00:24:39.680 --> 00:24:43.160
And film is incredibly
powerful for telling a message,

00:24:43.160 --> 00:24:45.613
whether it's a 30-second PSA.

00:24:45.613 --> 00:24:48.950
The "Blue Serengeti"
film that we showed,

00:24:48.950 --> 00:24:51.680
Barbara's film that we showed,
and had a wonderful panel

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:53.170
discussion about
that afterwards.

00:24:53.170 --> 00:24:55.670
DAVID HELVARG: Well, when and
where might you be doing this?

00:24:55.670 --> 00:24:57.230
ANA BLANCO: Thanks, David.

00:24:57.230 --> 00:25:00.350
The festival is coming
up in March 7 through 10.

00:25:00.350 --> 00:25:03.960
And it's at Cowell
Theater in San Francisco.

00:25:03.960 --> 00:25:06.110
So it's really an
opportunity for us

00:25:06.110 --> 00:25:08.960
to raise awareness
about the ocean.

00:25:08.960 --> 00:25:11.060
And there's something
for everyone,

00:25:11.060 --> 00:25:14.330
in terms of the myriad
topics that we cover.

00:25:14.330 --> 00:25:16.820
Because there's so many
issues in the ocean that

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:20.240
need to be talked about, not
only climate change, sea level

00:25:20.240 --> 00:25:25.490
rising, overfishing, mining,
drilling, sand dredging,

00:25:25.490 --> 00:25:26.390
marine wildlife.

00:25:26.390 --> 00:25:30.680
But we also show films that are
how we engage with the ocean,

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:33.770
and appreciate it, and have
fun with it, from surfing,

00:25:33.770 --> 00:25:36.860
and sailing, and the
joy that it brings us,

00:25:36.860 --> 00:25:39.530
and the peace and tranquility
that it brings us,

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:43.200
which is all the more
reason to protect it.

00:25:43.200 --> 00:25:47.240
But again, it's just like David
said, bringing people together

00:25:47.240 --> 00:25:49.760
who are like minded, who
have a common interest

00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:51.410
and want to do something.

00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:54.110
And until you learn
about what you can do,

00:25:54.110 --> 00:25:56.580
you're kind of at a
loss, so to speak.

00:25:56.580 --> 00:25:59.480
And so the films,
and David's Summit,

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:01.460
it's really just a
matter of getting engaged

00:26:01.460 --> 00:26:03.410
and finding out what's out
there and what's available.

00:26:03.410 --> 00:26:05.660
DAVID HELVARG: And last June
9th, Ana brought the film

00:26:05.660 --> 00:26:07.980
fest the night before, in DC.

00:26:07.980 --> 00:26:10.870
We had a first ever
march for the ocean.

00:26:10.870 --> 00:26:13.650
And the anchor march in DC
was only like 3,000 people,

00:26:13.650 --> 00:26:16.680
but there were 114 other marches
that happened around the world.

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:20.160
And we discovered that there's
this whole youthful cohort,

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:23.340
this sort of year class
of 10 to 18-year-olds,

00:26:23.340 --> 00:26:25.350
who are very engaged
round plastic.

00:26:25.350 --> 00:26:27.750
And so the Dublin march,
and 11-year-old activists

00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:29.850
led 500 people in Dublin.

00:26:29.850 --> 00:26:33.910
And out in the Pacific, there
was a 12 and a 16-year-old

00:26:33.910 --> 00:26:36.870
who organized that Chamorro
was on their island that

00:26:36.870 --> 00:26:40.910
then got hit by a typhoon
three months later.

00:26:40.910 --> 00:26:43.890
So people are-- and
we'll do it again

00:26:43.890 --> 00:26:45.360
on World Oceans Day, June 8th.

00:26:45.360 --> 00:26:48.090
But people are marching
for something that's

00:26:48.090 --> 00:26:49.290
immediately on top of them.

00:26:49.290 --> 00:26:52.950
I mean, what we saw with the
hurricane season of 2017,

00:26:52.950 --> 00:26:56.670
and then the climate
impacts with--

00:26:56.670 --> 00:26:59.490
I mean, I think 2018
was sort of the year

00:26:59.490 --> 00:27:03.160
of no denial between
Mexico Beach, Florida,

00:27:03.160 --> 00:27:05.230
and Paradise, California.

00:27:05.230 --> 00:27:08.010
And the ocean's the driver
of climate and weather,

00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:10.470
and takes it 90% of the
heat that we put out there.

00:27:10.470 --> 00:27:11.790
So it's key.

00:27:11.790 --> 00:27:16.425
Any climate solution has to
also be an ocean solution.

00:27:16.425 --> 00:27:18.300
BARBARA BLOCK: I mean,
there's another aspect

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:21.600
that we have to think about
that maybe someone in the Google

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:23.400
environment can help us with.

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.620
We're hunters and gatherers.

00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:28.200
And I ask my
students at Stanford

00:27:28.200 --> 00:27:31.680
all the time, how many are
planning your dinner a week

00:27:31.680 --> 00:27:32.740
from now?

00:27:32.740 --> 00:27:34.062
Anybody?

00:27:34.062 --> 00:27:37.195
I see one hand, one
hand in the audience.

00:27:37.195 --> 00:27:40.530
So how can we as a
species, that's really

00:27:40.530 --> 00:27:44.355
been focused on a very
short-term future,

00:27:44.355 --> 00:27:46.230
how do we get people to
worry about something

00:27:46.230 --> 00:27:51.660
that's going to be a disaster
less than 30 to 50 years away.

00:27:51.660 --> 00:27:55.960
And that's the challenge we
face as a species worldwide.

00:27:55.960 --> 00:27:58.852
And I think about this a lot.

00:27:58.852 --> 00:28:01.210
MICHIEL BAKKER: So maybe
just building upon this.

00:28:01.210 --> 00:28:04.650
So I believe that all of you
know extraordinarily well what

00:28:04.650 --> 00:28:08.310
the challenges are we're
faced with with the oceans.

00:28:08.310 --> 00:28:11.100
You probably have
clarity as well

00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:12.880
about what needs to get done.

00:28:12.880 --> 00:28:14.910
So maybe for the
audience, if you

00:28:14.910 --> 00:28:18.800
were in control, if you
had your magical wands,

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:20.880
what three elements
would you do?

00:28:20.880 --> 00:28:22.805
And how would you go about?

00:28:22.805 --> 00:28:24.180
So to me, it's a
question of what

00:28:24.180 --> 00:28:26.370
needs to get done,
but at the same time,

00:28:26.370 --> 00:28:28.950
how do you get it done
in today's very polarized

00:28:28.950 --> 00:28:30.370
environment?

00:28:30.370 --> 00:28:32.430
BARBARA BLOCK: I'll start.

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:33.540
I'm a researcher.

00:28:33.540 --> 00:28:36.960
And I get flabbergasted
at how small

00:28:36.960 --> 00:28:41.640
amount of money that is needed
right now to do some major push

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:43.710
forward in our ocean knowledge.

00:28:43.710 --> 00:28:45.960
So imagine a planet
where we haven't really

00:28:45.960 --> 00:28:48.080
explored the entire planet.

00:28:48.080 --> 00:28:53.250
We've got new technology in
DNA technology, bioinformatics,

00:28:53.250 --> 00:28:55.650
that allows us to
actually go in, take

00:28:55.650 --> 00:28:59.640
a Ziploc full of water,
and figure out who swam by.

00:28:59.640 --> 00:29:01.860
So we need to develop
these types of technologies

00:29:01.860 --> 00:29:04.110
to better census our oceans.

00:29:04.110 --> 00:29:08.160
We've got companies
across the planet that

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:11.460
are able to manage
data, like Google,

00:29:11.460 --> 00:29:15.240
and do an outstanding job of
bringing together big data.

00:29:15.240 --> 00:29:17.340
Right now, there's not
a big data platform

00:29:17.340 --> 00:29:20.520
for the oceans that
combines information

00:29:20.520 --> 00:29:23.610
in a way that makes it
accessible to both scientists

00:29:23.610 --> 00:29:24.300
and the public.

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:27.600
We need that big data
platform for our oceans

00:29:27.600 --> 00:29:29.620
as soon as possible.

00:29:29.620 --> 00:29:31.770
We need to develop
sensors, sensors

00:29:31.770 --> 00:29:34.440
that allow us to know
how the oxygen is

00:29:34.440 --> 00:29:38.010
changing in the ocean, how the
pH is changing in the ocean.

00:29:38.010 --> 00:29:40.110
And we need to have
these tomorrow.

00:29:40.110 --> 00:29:41.370
And they need to be cheap.

00:29:41.370 --> 00:29:42.730
And they need to be everywhere.

00:29:42.730 --> 00:29:45.780
So we have this
sort of bio-sensor

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:49.970
in the planet telling us what's
happening before it's too late.

00:29:49.970 --> 00:29:52.980
KYLE VAN HOUTAN:
Just to jump on that.

00:29:52.980 --> 00:29:56.580
Having automated
networked sensors,

00:29:56.580 --> 00:29:58.590
taking the research
that we do and applying

00:29:58.590 --> 00:30:01.650
the Internet of Things to it,
is desperately what we need.

00:30:01.650 --> 00:30:03.960
We just recently-- I'm
a researcher as well,

00:30:03.960 --> 00:30:05.760
and we just recently
put together

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:08.010
an analysis which is in
review right now, which

00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:11.730
is, in our view, is the
first ever global map

00:30:11.730 --> 00:30:14.150
of where all species
are on the planet,

00:30:14.150 --> 00:30:16.800
in land and in the ocean.

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:18.720
Usually, when you see
something like this,

00:30:18.720 --> 00:30:20.400
you see a picture of the land.

00:30:20.400 --> 00:30:21.960
And then the ocean
is grayed out.

00:30:21.960 --> 00:30:24.690
Or you see the picture of the
ocean, and land is grayed out.

00:30:24.690 --> 00:30:27.720
And what we've done, because
of data availability,

00:30:27.720 --> 00:30:29.670
is we've been able to
bring together something

00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:33.090
like 100,000 different species
and their distribution.

00:30:33.090 --> 00:30:36.450
And then, crucially, not just
say this is where they are,

00:30:36.450 --> 00:30:39.270
but use all the available
environmental data

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:43.020
to explain why those
species are where they are.

00:30:43.020 --> 00:30:44.440
Now this is a first step.

00:30:44.440 --> 00:30:48.300
This is, historically, this has
been a question for scientists

00:30:48.300 --> 00:30:50.020
for hundreds of years.

00:30:50.020 --> 00:30:52.290
But we've just had to
make progress iteratively

00:30:52.290 --> 00:30:55.110
by focusing on
certain species we

00:30:55.110 --> 00:30:58.128
know, like birds in certain
places, like South America.

00:30:58.128 --> 00:31:00.420
But we don't have to limit
ourselves that way any more.

00:31:00.420 --> 00:31:03.090
We can integrate everything,
like Barb's saying.

00:31:03.090 --> 00:31:06.120
But we certainly need the
data streams, the satellites,

00:31:06.120 --> 00:31:07.130
and to do that.

00:31:07.130 --> 00:31:09.360
Barb mentioned
environmental DNA,

00:31:09.360 --> 00:31:11.480
like having a
Ziploc bag of water.

00:31:11.480 --> 00:31:15.510
We're just about to install
essentially a robot,

00:31:15.510 --> 00:31:17.683
but it's a 50 gallon drum.

00:31:17.683 --> 00:31:20.100
And we're putting this in a
stream on the California coast

00:31:20.100 --> 00:31:24.390
to count salmon as they go by
and using environmental DNA

00:31:24.390 --> 00:31:25.320
to do that.

00:31:25.320 --> 00:31:29.460
This is revolutionary
technology that we desperately

00:31:29.460 --> 00:31:33.840
need to put on mobile
autonomous platforms and survey

00:31:33.840 --> 00:31:36.570
to the places that aren't
so near to the coast.

00:31:36.570 --> 00:31:39.360
Now we could send divers to
snorkel these streams and count

00:31:39.360 --> 00:31:39.860
fish.

00:31:39.860 --> 00:31:42.402
But wouldn't it be a lot easier
just to put a sensor in there

00:31:42.402 --> 00:31:43.030
and do that?

00:31:43.030 --> 00:31:44.460
And that's where
we are right now,

00:31:44.460 --> 00:31:45.793
the technology that we can have.

00:31:45.793 --> 00:31:48.215
And we're just starting to
scratch the surface with this.

00:31:48.215 --> 00:31:50.340
DAVID HELVARG: In a sense,
space technology's easy.

00:31:50.340 --> 00:31:53.130
There's a vacuum up there
and some micro meteorites.

00:31:53.130 --> 00:31:56.160
You know, the ocean is
this unbreathable corrosive

00:31:56.160 --> 00:31:59.100
liquid medium, with
upwellings, and surges,

00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:01.970
and storms, inaccessible,
biologicals,

00:32:01.970 --> 00:32:03.300
and all these challenges.

00:32:03.300 --> 00:32:04.830
We're reaching
that technology now

00:32:04.830 --> 00:32:08.490
and the media to actually
make the vast, everlasting sea

00:32:08.490 --> 00:32:10.140
accessible to us.

00:32:10.140 --> 00:32:12.330
But we're reaching it right
at that critical moment,

00:32:12.330 --> 00:32:15.750
where we're facing an
existential threat.

00:32:15.750 --> 00:32:18.840
And in the last century, we
faced two, the rise of fascism

00:32:18.840 --> 00:32:20.670
in the nuclear
balance of terror.

00:32:20.670 --> 00:32:22.380
And we got past them.

00:32:22.380 --> 00:32:23.850
Right now, because
of what Barbara

00:32:23.850 --> 00:32:27.060
said, because we don't
respond to long-term threats,

00:32:27.060 --> 00:32:29.430
we're seeing that it's
all foreshortened.

00:32:29.430 --> 00:32:31.710
And we're seeing the
threats in real time now.

00:32:31.710 --> 00:32:34.740
And so we need big,
dramatic responses.

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:37.710
We need to respond to the
threat of climate change,

00:32:37.710 --> 00:32:41.760
and marine pollution, and
loss of habitat at the level--

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:44.820
I live in Richmond Marina.

00:32:44.820 --> 00:32:47.790
My sailboat marina's where
they had Kaiser Shipyard Number

00:32:47.790 --> 00:32:52.690
Two, where they built 734
Liberty Ships in four years.

00:32:52.690 --> 00:32:55.620
So that kind of
industrial mobilization,

00:32:55.620 --> 00:32:58.660
the Manhattan Project, is
what we need right now.

00:32:58.660 --> 00:33:01.440
And what this new wave of young
women coming into Congress

00:33:01.440 --> 00:33:03.630
is proposing with
a Green New Deal.

00:33:03.630 --> 00:33:06.450
So we have to take all of
science, all the technology.

00:33:06.450 --> 00:33:09.160
And quite frankly, if
you look at our economy,

00:33:09.160 --> 00:33:12.370
we've got three major
sectors, sort of.

00:33:12.370 --> 00:33:14.580
The financial sector that
crashed the world economy

00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:16.110
in 2008.

00:33:16.110 --> 00:33:18.450
We've got the oil and gas
industry, the fossil fuel

00:33:18.450 --> 00:33:21.090
industry, that's literally
crashing the world.

00:33:21.090 --> 00:33:22.500
And then the tech
industry, based

00:33:22.500 --> 00:33:26.400
in California, which for
all the problems you've got,

00:33:26.400 --> 00:33:30.060
is producing goods and services
with technological capability

00:33:30.060 --> 00:33:31.530
to understand threats.

00:33:31.530 --> 00:33:34.800
And now we need to mobilize
large parts of our population

00:33:34.800 --> 00:33:36.580
to respond to those threats.

00:33:36.580 --> 00:33:39.300
We did it twice in
the last century.

00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:41.377
We'll do something in this one.

00:33:41.377 --> 00:33:43.710
MICHIEL BAKKER: Birgitte or
Ana, any additional thoughts

00:33:43.710 --> 00:33:44.340
from you?

00:33:44.340 --> 00:33:47.340
BIRGITTE RASINE: Yes, some
years ago, I wrote a report

00:33:47.340 --> 00:33:48.720
on responsibility in the media.

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:51.490
And I actually got to interview
Andy Rifkin of "The New York

00:33:51.490 --> 00:33:51.990
Times."

00:33:51.990 --> 00:33:55.140
He's a top scientist,
science reporter.

00:33:55.140 --> 00:33:58.227
And I asked him, because
I was at the time

00:33:58.227 --> 00:33:59.310
working on climate change.

00:33:59.310 --> 00:34:02.130
And I asked him
why is it that we

00:34:02.130 --> 00:34:05.490
find we find it so
hard to understand

00:34:05.490 --> 00:34:07.530
and kind of embody in
ourselves an understanding

00:34:07.530 --> 00:34:08.400
of climate change?

00:34:08.400 --> 00:34:10.679
And he said, it's very simple.

00:34:10.679 --> 00:34:14.190
We don't teach our young
people how to think critically.

00:34:14.190 --> 00:34:17.159
We do not teach at the
elementary school level

00:34:17.159 --> 00:34:20.820
or up until you, basically
until you get to university,

00:34:20.820 --> 00:34:25.610
we don't teach basic scientific
understanding and thinking.

00:34:25.610 --> 00:34:28.440
He said, if we can-- so if I
had my magic wand, I would do--

00:34:28.440 --> 00:34:30.540
can I have two magic wands?

00:34:30.540 --> 00:34:31.659
I would do two things.

00:34:31.659 --> 00:34:34.770
I wouldn't first introduce a
study of maybe scuba diving

00:34:34.770 --> 00:34:38.350
as a required curriculum in
coastal states, something

00:34:38.350 --> 00:34:38.850
like that.

00:34:38.850 --> 00:34:40.900
We need to bring it
down to that level.

00:34:40.900 --> 00:34:43.020
And second, popular culture.

00:34:43.020 --> 00:34:46.260
Popular culture, like can we
have a Blue Panther movie?

00:34:46.260 --> 00:34:52.110
Can we have Coral Sponge Bob,
or coral whatever his name is?

00:34:52.110 --> 00:34:53.862
So I think we need
to tell more stories.

00:34:53.862 --> 00:34:54.945
DAVID HELVARG: Carl Coral.

00:34:54.945 --> 00:34:55.330
BIRGITTE RASINE: What?

00:34:55.330 --> 00:34:55.690
DAVID HELVARG: Carl Coral.

00:34:55.690 --> 00:34:58.000
BIRGITTE RASINE: There
you go, Carl Coral.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:34:59.280
Hollywood, you listening?

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:01.600
So I think we need
to tell more stories.

00:35:01.600 --> 00:35:04.200
And I don't mean kind
of didactic, beat them

00:35:04.200 --> 00:35:06.600
over the head
about, maybe there's

00:35:06.600 --> 00:35:10.560
a movie about coral bleaching or
something like that, not that.

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:13.740
But somehow find
stories that take

00:35:13.740 --> 00:35:17.190
the mythology and the
fascination with the ocean,

00:35:17.190 --> 00:35:19.440
because God knows, you
go down deep enough

00:35:19.440 --> 00:35:22.137
and it's all science
fiction down there.

00:35:22.137 --> 00:35:23.970
BARBARA BLOCK: You're
raising a great issue.

00:35:23.970 --> 00:35:26.910
It's one that just Friday we
were discussing at Stanford.

00:35:26.910 --> 00:35:30.150
So there really is an
ocean literacy problem.

00:35:30.150 --> 00:35:32.280
I'm working on a
project right now trying

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:35.010
to think about at
the collegiate level

00:35:35.010 --> 00:35:37.420
how to bring about
ocean literacy.

00:35:37.420 --> 00:35:40.230
We also are working
with Aspen High Seas,

00:35:40.230 --> 00:35:44.040
trying to figure out if we could
do an ocean conservation corps.

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:45.690
So what if there
was a way to get

00:35:45.690 --> 00:35:50.670
youth engaged at a very
early age, that was global.

00:35:50.670 --> 00:35:53.700
So I think that we've done a
lot of that in our land ethic.

00:35:53.700 --> 00:35:55.560
But we've done a
little less, because

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:58.050
of its inaccessibility,
the high seas,

00:35:58.050 --> 00:36:00.030
places like that, for oceans.

00:36:00.030 --> 00:36:03.840
But it really begins
at the basic problem

00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:06.480
of teaching how oceans work.

00:36:06.480 --> 00:36:08.700
So if you went down the
street in a beautiful place

00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:12.180
like Monterey, and I asked
four individuals, well,

00:36:12.180 --> 00:36:15.465
what's the basic concept of
how oceans and atmosphere

00:36:15.465 --> 00:36:17.910
or oceans, and
climate, or even just

00:36:17.910 --> 00:36:21.670
oceans, what do you think
about how they work?

00:36:21.670 --> 00:36:25.170
And I don't think we'd get very
clear answers, because we leave

00:36:25.170 --> 00:36:26.640
it out of our basic education.

00:36:26.640 --> 00:36:29.160
We leave biosphere
out of our education.

00:36:29.160 --> 00:36:31.410
So what we're thinking
about at our university is,

00:36:31.410 --> 00:36:33.060
how do we get it back in?

00:36:33.060 --> 00:36:35.310
And how do we make it so
accessible that a business

00:36:35.310 --> 00:36:38.670
student, an English major,
or anybody who wants

00:36:38.670 --> 00:36:40.020
to learn about the planet.

00:36:40.020 --> 00:36:43.470
We do it right now through a
course called Stanford at Sea.

00:36:43.470 --> 00:36:46.860
It's related to Sea Education
Association of Woods Hole.

00:36:46.860 --> 00:36:50.040
These are opportunities for
high school, college students

00:36:50.040 --> 00:36:52.890
to actually have an
immersion experience.

00:36:52.890 --> 00:36:55.815
But we need more people to
engage in that immersion.

00:36:55.815 --> 00:36:57.940
ANA BLANCO: And along those
lines, at the festival,

00:36:57.940 --> 00:37:01.530
like when you mentioned
that, Barbara, you just

00:37:01.530 --> 00:37:02.790
made me think.

00:37:02.790 --> 00:37:05.890
Ocean literacy is
kind of a new concept.

00:37:05.890 --> 00:37:09.720
And it's not introduced in
middle school or high school

00:37:09.720 --> 00:37:10.670
level.

00:37:10.670 --> 00:37:14.970
And it's such an important
part of our education.

00:37:14.970 --> 00:37:18.480
And I think it's becoming more
and more critical to reach kids

00:37:18.480 --> 00:37:19.770
at that particular age.

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:24.110
And like you said, it needs
to be on a global level.

00:37:24.110 --> 00:37:27.960
At the festival, we do a free
program for middle school

00:37:27.960 --> 00:37:31.590
and high school students to
come and see the films for free.

00:37:31.590 --> 00:37:34.230
And so many of the teachers
are so excited about it,

00:37:34.230 --> 00:37:38.550
because they just don't have
the time or the bandwidth

00:37:38.550 --> 00:37:42.400
to include something like ocean
literacy in their program.

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:44.970
So they use the films
as an opportunity

00:37:44.970 --> 00:37:47.410
to get the kids
excited about that.

00:37:47.410 --> 00:37:49.230
We also have a student
film competition.

00:37:49.230 --> 00:37:52.670
Kids all over the world send in
a film, five minutes or less,

00:37:52.670 --> 00:37:54.780
that tell us about the ocean.

00:37:54.780 --> 00:37:57.780
We use the Monterey Bay
Aquarium, has great career

00:37:57.780 --> 00:37:59.810
online for ocean literacy.

00:37:59.810 --> 00:38:02.300
But I don't think
we can stress enough

00:38:02.300 --> 00:38:06.500
how much we need to start
engaging really young kids,

00:38:06.500 --> 00:38:08.690
at the middle school
and high school level,

00:38:08.690 --> 00:38:11.330
to start thinking about this
and make it a part of our core

00:38:11.330 --> 00:38:12.180
curriculum.

00:38:12.180 --> 00:38:13.805
DAVID HELVARG: And
one of our projects,

00:38:13.805 --> 00:38:15.500
Blue Frontier
projects in this year,

00:38:15.500 --> 00:38:18.500
2019, is a Blue
Beat program, which

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:22.550
is just basic idea that the
only resource not fully explored

00:38:22.550 --> 00:38:24.700
in the ocean is
good storytelling.

00:38:24.700 --> 00:38:27.050
