trainings for scientists,

00:38:27.050 --> 00:38:30.230
like we've done at IUCN.

00:38:30.230 --> 00:38:33.740
Also just grassroots
activists, to understand

00:38:33.740 --> 00:38:36.110
how to talk to a journalists,
how to tell stories,

00:38:36.110 --> 00:38:39.860
how to use the tools
at hand, our phones

00:38:39.860 --> 00:38:42.170
and otherwise, to produce.

00:38:42.170 --> 00:38:44.120
Not to do campaigns,
to tell stories.

00:38:44.120 --> 00:38:45.830
Because that's what
connects with people.

00:38:45.830 --> 00:38:48.650
And it's instinctual
with our young activists,

00:38:48.650 --> 00:38:51.230
they're all using those tools.

00:38:51.230 --> 00:38:52.820
But it's a challenge.

00:38:52.820 --> 00:38:56.060
I want to translate "50 Ways
to Save the Ocean," to Spanish,

00:38:56.060 --> 00:38:57.750
as one of the immediate needs.

00:38:57.750 --> 00:38:59.890
So it's not Carl,
it's Carlos the Coral.

00:39:02.065 --> 00:39:03.440
KYLE VAN HOUTAN:
The storytelling

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:04.650
is absolutely critical.

00:39:04.650 --> 00:39:07.220
I mean, I'm a
researcher at heart,

00:39:07.220 --> 00:39:10.100
but I try to be, I
try to tell stories.

00:39:10.100 --> 00:39:14.330
And anything from the "Book
of Jonah" to "Moby Dick,"

00:39:14.330 --> 00:39:18.050
the ocean has captivated our
imagination for millennia.

00:39:18.050 --> 00:39:22.010
And obviously, it's our goal at
the aquarium to inspire people

00:39:22.010 --> 00:39:23.220
about the ocean.

00:39:23.220 --> 00:39:25.650
We get about two
million visitors a year.

00:39:25.650 --> 00:39:27.995
And most of them,
geographically,

00:39:27.995 --> 00:39:29.870
or because of their own
physical limitations,

00:39:29.870 --> 00:39:32.370
cannot actually
go into the ocean.

00:39:32.370 --> 00:39:33.590
They're from Kansas.

00:39:33.590 --> 00:39:36.700
Or they have
physical limitations.

00:39:36.700 --> 00:39:39.290
And so one of the
amazing things for us

00:39:39.290 --> 00:39:41.960
is to see the transformation
that people have

00:39:41.960 --> 00:39:44.570
when they go in the
door to when they leave.

00:39:44.570 --> 00:39:47.780
And yesterday, two days
ago, Saturday morning,

00:39:47.780 --> 00:39:51.140
I was speaking to a hundred
elementary and middle school

00:39:51.140 --> 00:39:53.628
science teachers in the
State of California.

00:39:53.628 --> 00:39:55.670
And everything that we've
been saying right here,

00:39:55.670 --> 00:39:59.330
we just need to inculcate
these ideas into curriculum

00:39:59.330 --> 00:40:01.020
in public schools.

00:40:01.020 --> 00:40:02.690
So that is not
like an exception,

00:40:02.690 --> 00:40:06.560
but it is the norm, that people
have a first-hand experience

00:40:06.560 --> 00:40:09.440
of the ocean and what it is,
as well as strong curriculum

00:40:09.440 --> 00:40:10.910
in math and science.

00:40:10.910 --> 00:40:12.200
It absolutely has to happen.

