00:41:32.630 --> 00:41:35.480
AUDIENCE: Given the volume
of plastic currently produced

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:39.140
in the world, which is about
300 million tons per year,

00:41:39.140 --> 00:41:42.660
since the 1950s, it
just went exponentially,

00:41:42.660 --> 00:41:45.240
I heard that it's probably
going to double by 2050.

00:41:45.240 --> 00:41:48.050
So has anyone kind of
modeled out what an ocean's

00:41:48.050 --> 00:41:51.135
going to look like in 2050?

00:41:51.135 --> 00:41:52.760
KYLE VAN HOUTAN: I'll
jump on that one,

00:41:52.760 --> 00:41:55.280
because we've been
looking at this question.

00:41:55.280 --> 00:41:59.610
So if you remember, one of
the first scientific sort

00:41:59.610 --> 00:42:01.550
of pieces of
information which led

00:42:01.550 --> 00:42:03.290
to our understanding
of climate change

00:42:03.290 --> 00:42:06.410
was Charles Keeling's
CO2 curve from the top

00:42:06.410 --> 00:42:08.330
of Mount Aloha in Hawaii.

00:42:08.330 --> 00:42:10.760
And that showed the
oscillating annual atmospheric

00:42:10.760 --> 00:42:12.440
concentration of CO2.

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:14.510
And it wasn't just
seasonally moving around,

00:42:14.510 --> 00:42:15.920
it was trending upwards.

00:42:15.920 --> 00:42:17.510
That started about 1958.

00:42:17.510 --> 00:42:21.620
And I think that was a very
important piece of science

00:42:21.620 --> 00:42:25.790
that led us to say, wait a
second, this is a problem.

00:42:25.790 --> 00:42:28.070
We don't have that
right now for plastic.

00:42:28.070 --> 00:42:29.840
We don't have a Keeling Curve.

00:42:29.840 --> 00:42:31.890
We're working on
understanding that.

00:42:31.890 --> 00:42:33.830
But one of the things
that we toss around

00:42:33.830 --> 00:42:35.990
is, with respect
to climate change,

00:42:35.990 --> 00:42:38.600
if we could magically turn off
the spigot of carbon dioxide

00:42:38.600 --> 00:42:40.100
and greenhouse gas
equivalents, we'd

00:42:40.100 --> 00:42:43.010
probably be dealing with climate
change for about 1,000 years,

00:42:43.010 --> 00:42:45.860
just because of how convoluted
the earth's climate system is.

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:48.560
If we could magically turn
off the spigot for plastic,

00:42:48.560 --> 00:42:50.960
how much longer would we
have plastic in the ocean?

00:42:50.960 --> 00:42:53.840
I think it's far less,
probably around 50 years.

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:57.520
So I'm much more
hopeful about the change

00:42:57.520 --> 00:42:58.930
that we can make with plastic.

00:42:58.930 --> 00:43:00.705
Yes, you are correct
that we are--

00:43:00.705 --> 00:43:02.830
and by the way, the plastic
and the climate problem

00:43:02.830 --> 00:43:03.760
are not unrelated.

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:06.500
Because plastic is made
out of petrochemicals.

00:43:06.500 --> 00:43:09.260
So it is an oil based,
for the most part.

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:12.280
There is a recycled and there
is agricultural based products.

00:43:12.280 --> 00:43:15.792
But probably around 50 years,
if we could cut it off today.

00:43:15.792 --> 00:43:17.750
But there's more and more
going into the ocean.

00:43:17.750 --> 00:43:20.020
So it's clearly a very
significant problem.

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:23.935
But we don't yet know how
big a problem that is.

00:43:23.935 --> 00:43:25.060
We need that Keeling Curve.

00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:27.143
DAVID HELVARG: But they're
all linked to rock oil.

00:43:27.143 --> 00:43:28.510
They're all linked to petroleum.

00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:30.580
The off shore
drilling, the plastics,

00:43:30.580 --> 00:43:34.280
the protection of
our shores at risk.

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:35.680
We just need to move on.

00:43:35.680 --> 00:43:37.930
I mean coal and oil were
great energy systems

00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:41.660
for the 16th and 19th century.

00:43:41.660 --> 00:43:43.840
Now it's, as I said,
it's a product liability,

00:43:43.840 --> 00:43:45.880
used as directed it
spoils everything.

00:43:45.880 --> 00:43:49.960
So let's move on and
do what we did after--

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:53.320
when Rockwell replaced whale
oil, the economy expanded.

00:43:53.320 --> 00:43:55.690
With the Green New Deal,
it's going to expand again.

00:43:55.690 --> 00:43:58.855
We'll have jobs and clean
future if we choose to.

00:43:58.855 --> 00:44:01.480
BIRGITTE RASINE: And there's an
upstream and downstream problem

00:44:01.480 --> 00:44:01.980
too.

00:44:01.980 --> 00:44:04.453
So it's how much plastic
are we producing?

00:44:04.453 --> 00:44:06.870
From what I understand, some
of the big plastic producers,

00:44:06.870 --> 00:44:10.180
all the single use cups, and
tubs, and all that stuff,

00:44:10.180 --> 00:44:13.840
apparently they want to produce
more, which is a big problem.

00:44:13.840 --> 00:44:16.720
And on the other side is,
let's clean up what we've got.

00:44:16.720 --> 00:44:20.830
So you guys probably heard
of Boyan Slat and System 001.

00:44:20.830 --> 00:44:24.430
So he's trying right now to
clean up the Great Pacific

00:44:24.430 --> 00:44:26.310
Garbage Patch.

00:44:26.310 --> 00:44:28.095
And there's controversy,
meaning, well,

00:44:28.095 --> 00:44:29.470
why are you focusing
on that when

00:44:29.470 --> 00:44:31.970
you should be focusing on
upstream and the manufacturer?

00:44:31.970 --> 00:44:33.760
I think we really
need to do both.

00:44:33.760 --> 00:44:36.640
Because you need-- it's like
you've messed up your room.

00:44:36.640 --> 00:44:38.320
Well, you've got to
clean up your room

00:44:38.320 --> 00:44:41.380
and then see if you can find
more sustainable toys to fill

00:44:41.380 --> 00:44:41.880
it with.

00:44:41.880 --> 00:44:43.672
MICHIEL BAKKER: One
question from the Dory.

00:44:43.672 --> 00:44:45.630
When it comes to
sensing ocean data,

00:44:45.630 --> 00:44:47.380
can you talk a little
about the difference

00:44:47.380 --> 00:44:50.410
in data needed in comparison to
what we can measure with Earth

00:44:50.410 --> 00:44:52.480
observation satellites?

00:44:52.480 --> 00:44:54.970
What is the role of EO
satellites in building

00:44:54.970 --> 00:44:57.130
our understanding of the ocean?

00:44:57.130 --> 00:44:59.410
BARBARA BLOCK: So the
Earth's satellite system

00:44:59.410 --> 00:45:01.810
has done a fantastic
job of telling us

00:45:01.810 --> 00:45:05.740
about the skin of the
ocean, the surface.

00:45:05.740 --> 00:45:09.110
But the volume of the
ocean is much larger.

00:45:09.110 --> 00:45:13.682
And so we know a lot about
the top portion of the ocean,

00:45:13.682 --> 00:45:15.390
but we don't know a
lot about the depths.

00:45:15.390 --> 00:45:19.200
And part of the mystery
of Earth's circulation

00:45:19.200 --> 00:45:24.120
is that without knowing the
conditions beneath the sea,

00:45:24.120 --> 00:45:28.330
and by not having a complete
sensor system on the planet,

00:45:28.330 --> 00:45:31.500
we have surprises that
are going to happen.

00:45:31.500 --> 00:45:36.360
So I believe that it'll
be in this next 50 years

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:39.360
that we do a very remarkable
job of instrumenting

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:42.850
the oceans, which has been
behind the rest of the planet.

00:45:42.850 --> 00:45:47.040
And we're going to do it
with cheap, small sensors,

00:45:47.040 --> 00:45:49.890
that we have to figure out how
to seed the ocean currents,

00:45:49.890 --> 00:45:51.985
without creating, if
you will, pollution.

00:45:51.985 --> 00:45:54.360
We're going to do it with a
series of buoys, and gliders,

00:45:54.360 --> 00:45:58.080
and all sorts of instrumentation
we could only imagine.

00:45:58.080 --> 00:46:01.980
And we're going to need
big data companies who

00:46:01.980 --> 00:46:04.980
are committed to
making it public data,

00:46:04.980 --> 00:46:08.220
being behind these efforts,
and then contributing

00:46:08.220 --> 00:46:11.280
to this incredible analysis
that has to happen,

00:46:11.280 --> 00:46:13.792
that will increase our
understanding of our planet.

